    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - HUBS, BEARINGS, AND SEALS - HUB ASSEMBLY</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>HUB ASSEMBLY</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="clean" graphiccount="5">
            <title>CLEAN AND INSPECT</title>
            <para>Clean hub with mineral solvent and air pressure dry. Check assembly for:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Worn Stud Holes (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400130">Figure 32</hotlnk>). This condition is caused by stud turning in the hole
                    because of insufficient torque on the inner nut (stud). Replace hub.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400130" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400130" filename="../figg14/g1400130.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="192px" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 32. Worn Stud Holes</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Worn Mounting Face (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400131">Figure 33</hotlnk>). This condition is caused by a loose wheel assembly
                    with outboard mounted drum. The outer mounting face of the brake drum is worn. Replace hub or brake
                    drum.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400131" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400131" filename="../figg14/g1400131.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 33. Worn Mounting Face</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Broken or Stripped Threads Wheel Stud (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400132">Figure 34</hotlnk>and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400133">Figure 35</hotlnk>) Replace studs.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400132" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400132" filename="../figg14/g1400132.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 34. Broken Threads</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f1400133" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400133" filename="../figg14/g1400133.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 35. Stripped Threads</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Porous Condition Where Leakage May Occur. Replace hub.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Bent Hub Face (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400134">Figure 36</hotlnk>). This condition can be caused by wheels running loose
                    for an extended period of time. Continual retightening of wheel nuts is an indication of bent hub;
                    hub should be checked. If there is more than a 1/32 inch gap as shown in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400134">Figure 36</hotlnk>, replace hub.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400134" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400134" filename="../figg14/g1400134.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="272px" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 36. Checking for Bent Hub Face</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. STRAIGHT EDGE</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. HUB</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. GAP BETWEEN HUB FACE AND STRAIGHT EDGE</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
